    "body": "## Problem\r\n\r\nWhen running nvim on a remote machine over ssh, if there is high ping, then bg detection may not complete in time. This results in a warning every time nvim is started. Some users have issues with the warning whose causes are not yet clear. #38648\r\n\r\n## Solution\r\n\r\nAdd environment variable option to disable waiting for bg detection during startup (`NVIM_NO_BG_WAIT`) and another option which allows waiting for bg detection but suppresses the warning (`NVIM_NO_BG_WAIT_WARNING`). These options are environment variables rather than config options because the bg detection occurs before user config.\r\n\r\nI think the variables should be documented somewhere other than news, but I'm not sure where to put them.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "comment_data": [],
    "comment_regular_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "Thanks for your effort here. But env vars aren't the right approach. In the worst case, we can:\r\n\r\n- document how to delete the autocmd that does this work,\r\n    - assign a dedicated augroup so that the user can surgically remove only that handler?\r\n- and/or move the logic to somewhere like `runtime/lua/vim/tty.lua`, and the user can nuke it via `tty.foo = function()end`.\r\n\r\nSo those are near-term steps we can take. \r\n\r\nThe ideal/long-term approach is to either detect the conditions where we shouldn't wait (depends on if we found any such conditions in https://github.com/neovim/neovim/discussions/38648 ), or increase the wait.\r\n\r\nWe could also consider restoring 'ttyfast', and if that option is disabled then we could change behavior for things like this.\r\n\r\n- https://github.com/neovim/neovim/issues/1045",
