        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "> document how to delete the autocmd that does this work\r\n\r\n> and/or move the logic to somewhere like `runtime/lua/vim/tty.lua`, and the user can nuke it via `tty.foo = function()end`.\r\n\r\n> We could also consider restoring 'ttyfast', and if that option is disabled then we could change behavior for things like this.\r\n\r\nLike @zeertzjq said, this executes directly in `defaults.lua` and waits to complete before processing config, so I don't think any of these will work.\r\n\r\n> The ideal/long-term approach is to either detect the conditions where we shouldn't wait (depends on if we found any such conditions in #38648 ), or increase the wait.\r\n\r\nIf we just look at the ssh example, I'm not sure how we can detect it. It's just nvim running on a remote machine in any environment. If I ssh into a server with 500 ping, then the `vim.wait` could last the whole time, time out, and then allow startup to continue (also generating a warning). This would add a 100 ms delay to startup every time, and if we increase the wait, it only gets worse. I can see some users opting for no delay even if it means some flickering or minor syntax highlighting bugs.\r\n\r\nOne option is to move the logic into a function like `tty.bg_detect()` and force the user to run it in their own config early on to detect the bg before processing the rest of their config. I'm not sure if this could bring back some of the bugs in syntax highlighting due to the change in sequence, and this would be a breaking change.\r\n\r\nI guess another option is just to remove the warning.\r\n\r\nStill looking for the root cause for the user that wasn't using ssh, but at least for ssh, I think it makes sense to make it optional.",
