        {
            "author_association": "CONTRIBUTOR",
            "body": "`$TERM` is just relying on another environment variable, but that also doesn't solve the ssh latency problem because they can be using any terminal over ssh (unless we instruct users to set `$TERM` to something special to indicate it's ssh, which will break other programs).\r\n\r\nIf we really don't want to use environment variables, we could try something like:\r\n- Send DSR\r\n- Wait up to 5ms for response\r\n- If we don't get a response in time, assume high latency environment or DSR unsupported\r\n  - In this case, we can still send the bg query but skip the `vim.wait`\r\n- If we do get a response in time, we're in a supported environment\r\n  - In this case, send bg query and use another `vim.wait()` to ensure BG is set properly before processing user config\r\n\r\nThis leads to a max startup delay of about 5ms if DSR isn't answered. However, in those cases, it again leads to the UI bugs that the `vim.wait()` resolved, with the user having no choice over it.",
            "created_at": "2026-04-03T15:05:31Z",
